  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Mary Anne Estlin says that contributions for the [anti-slavery] bazaar have been sent to Liverpool for shipping; they are more numerous and more heterogeneous than those of previous years. There were 535 people, besides four schools, who visited the collection of articles when it was on view; the visitors were mostly the contributors and their friends. William Lloyd Garrison&apos;s departure caused sadness. &quot;We have to fight a great many battles for him&quot; with those who know him only through the published reports of his speeches. If Garrison&apos;s course is the best for America, &quot;we shall be less grieved at his having failed to enlist the sympathies of many in England who are not hostile to the cause.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In the postscript, Mary Anne Estlin calls attention to the articles made by pupils of the &quot;Blind Asylum.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
